Anonymous Sun 26 Feb 2023 16:19:31 No.54695054 Report
Quoted By: >>54695100
>>54694103
>>54694136
The danger in this is leaving out too much. What you think is enough might not be.
I've gotten into writing much shorter non-dialogue paragraphs the longer I've been at it. And anytime they aren't moving or emoting during dialogue, it gets summarized.
A third trick I've been using is to draft, then break down scenes. I want what I tell and show to dovetail. If you were me, that wordy feeling is that I've got a section that could be moved, summarized, or deleted.

But then again, I've been accused, simultaneously, of being too wordy and too terse. Perhaps it's because I'm a bit older than the average here and learned to read at home.

And to add on, two that I use...
Ruiadh - someone caught the reference on this for Marlowe, but it translates to red.
Reynard - this story cycle has been a huge influence on Marlowe, and by coincidence is also the word for fox in French.

And one that might feature in the latter books is cyon. It's a common part of many canid species names on both the canine & vulpine branches.

You could go really exotic and look up the words for fox in various Native American languages, especially if you are doing a fantasy setting with magic
